{"questionId":"19871","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The rate of change of the height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>)</mo></math> of a ball above horizontal ground, measured in metres,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds after it has been thrown and until it hits the ground, can be modelled by the&nbsp;equation</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:60px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>t</mi></math></p>\n<p>The height of the ball when&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the range of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Maximum value is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83061</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>(M1)</strong></p>\n<p>Range is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>A1A1</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>83</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[3 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19871","referenceCode":"EXN.2.SL.TZ0.3c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the range of h.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.2—Functions, notation domain, range and inverse as reflection"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}